\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring Kryo subclassing**\\n\\nI'm thinking about testing ClosureSerializer for read/write/copy functionality without depending on Kryo's FieldSerializer. This could involve subclassing Kryo and overriding the writeObject/readObject methods to manage replacements. However, I noticed that the write method uses reflection in the library to access private methods, then calls kryo.writeObject. I need to check if writeObject in Kryo is final or if I can extend it. Inspecting this will help clarify my approach.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_dracR2gysakDpY7GeaLgTJ2P|fc_0f11957e5262e9c20169f27f2f32e881a3a94e6e20ee4d56db", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg -n \"void writeObject|<T> T readObject|Object readObject\" /home/jovan/Work/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/com.esotericsoftware/kryo-shaded/3.0.3/main/extracted/com/esotericsoftware/kryo/Kryo.java | head -80", "timeout": 10}, "partialJson": "{\"command\":\"rg -n \\\"void writeObject|<T> T readObject|Object readObject\\\" /home/jovan/Work/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/com.esotericsoftware/kryo-shaded/3.0.3/main/extracted/com/esotericsoftware/kryo/Kryo.java | head -80\",\"timeout\":10}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 6110, "output": 1211, "cacheRead": 29696, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 37017, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777499931688, "responseId": "resp_0f11957e5262e9c20169f27f1c75e481a383d9cb0d474672c3"}}
